	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Trade policy: WTO Papua New Guinea Trade Policy Review</h1>

			
			<h4>
												01 March 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to the WTO Secretariat’s review of the trade policy of Papua New Guinea, agriculture accounts for around a quarter of GDP, and consists largely of subsistence and semi-subsistence farmers, growing mostly ‘sweet potato, banana, yam, cassava, taro, coconuts, sugar cane, maize and peanuts. Smallholder farmers ‘produce almost all food consumed in PNG and over 80% of exported crops (e.g. coffee, cocoa, copra and vanilla).’ There are also large plantations growing palm oil, coffee, cocoa, coconut, tea and rubber.</p><p>In 2009, farm products accounted for 18.7% of total merchandise exports. The agrarian economy, however, is ‘vulnerable to the effects of international commodity price fluctuations’. The agricultural sector also suffers from low yields and productivity, with this leading to a decline in export volumes. The only exception to this trend is palm oil, where production has expanded from 32,000 tonnes in 2003 to 446,000 tonnes in 2008, based on core estates and out-growers.</p><p>The government of Papua New Guinea (PNG) sees the agricultural sector as ‘a key sector in promoting export-driven growth, rural development, and poverty reduction.’ Food security, meaning self-sufficiency (including in processed foods), is accorded high priority by government. Tariff protection is relatively high for agricultural products: using high levels of tariff protection, the country is ‘almost self-sufficient in sugar, pork and chicken’. The sugar sector, however, is highly inefficient, and could well face viability problems when tariff protection falls to 40% in 2011 (previously 70%).</p><p>The WTO review notes that the food-processing sector is facing a process of tariff dismantling, in line with the general trend towards tariff liberalisation. Tariff reform and liberalisation has been taking place since 2000, although applied agricultural tariffs (on average 12.8% since 2008) remain higher than for non-agricultural products, with overall some 77% of tariff lines being duty free. A notable exception to this trend is the poultry sector, which has expanded rapidly, ‘initially under protection from an import ban, and more recently due to high specific tariff on frozen chicken of K2.20 per kg’. Some non-specific duties hide relatively high tariff rates. In addition, with a bound tariff rate averaging 32.8%, the government retains scope to raise tariffs within its WTO commitments.</p><p>In terms of agricultural trade policy, a National Agricultural Development Plan has been launched for the period 2007-2016, with an annual financial allocation of K100m (US$35.3m). The principal aim of government agricultural policy is ‘the domestication of value-added in agriculture’. The government of PNG makes no use of import quotas and has only minimal import-licensing arrangements, although there are prohibitions on ‘imports of uncooked poultry products, eggs, and licensing restrictions on cooked and processed poultry products’.</p><p>With the exception of palm oil, major export crops are marketed through statutory bodies, which, it is argued by the WTO Secretariat, ‘may have impeded agricultural development through inefficiency and over-regulation’. Statutory bodies in various ways control the issuing of export licences, which often favours firms with strong local participation. Some statutory bodies can reject contracts if prices are significantly below prevailing market price levels. In certain sectors (e.g. coffee), efforts are under way to work with private sector companies to improve coffee quality and to target ‘luxury purchase’ markets, with some 1% of PNG coffee exports (by value) being traded in fair-trade markets.</p><p>Under its IEPA, PNG has agreed to eliminate tariffs immediately on 82.1% of tariff lines. This covers 88.1% of imports from the EU. These tariff lines involve products which are either zero-rated at the MFN level, or on which no trade with the EU takes place. Sensitive products, such as meat and vegetables, are however excluded from these tariff reduction commitments. In addition, ‘quantitative restrictions as well as import and export licences are prohibited from the outset’ as are ‘internal quantitative regulations on the mixture, processing or use of domestically sourced products in specified amounts or proportions’.</p><p>In responding to the WTO review, the government notes that the country’s ‘trade policy has focused primarily on tariff liberalisation, removal of non-tariff barriers to trade, providing tariff protection for specific local industries and undertaking negotiations on trade agreements.’ This is operationalised through ‘appropriate interventions on imports and enhancing market access for exports’. The government claims that it ‘maintains no import quotas, export licences, or tariff rate quotas’. It argues that the conclusion of an IEPA with the EU was necessary to ensure preferential access for canned tuna exports.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
WTO, Trade Policy Review for Papua New Guinea, point of access for all sections of the report, 16-18 November 2010 <br/>
<a href="http://www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/tpr_e/tp339_e.htm" target="_self">http://www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/tpr_e/tp339_e.htm</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>It is unclear what impact the IEPA prohibition on the use of import and export licences will have on the operation of statutory bodies which issue these import and export licences in line with government policy objectives, and it will be up to the government of Papua New Guinea to decide whether or not to amend its import licensing arrangements. Some experts take the view that since few imports from the EU are affected, it is unlikely the EU will raise an objection to the continued use of these agricultural trade-policy tools, in the context of the generalised shift towards trade liberalisation.</p><p>Similarly, with regard to the government’s export-licensing regime, this policy tool is largely used to promote value-added processing activities (e.g. for cooked and processed poultry products), an important policy objective for the government of PNG (i.e. ‘the domestication of value added in agriculture’). While these arrangements could be affected by the prohibition in the IEPA on import and export-licensing arrangements, the government of PNG may be able to make continued use of this policy tool if EU interests are not affected.</p><p>A review of PNG’s schedule of tariff-reduction commitments and other market-opening commitments would appear necessary to ascertain whether existing regulations and policy measures need to be reconciled with the IEPA commitments, or whether apparent inconsistencies can simply be left to stand.</p><p>Against this background, the experience in other ACP regions related to the continued tolerance of the use of import- and export-licensing arrangements may prove illuminating (e.g. the ongoing discussions in the SADC-EU EPA negotiations).</p>
		</div>
		
